1
00:00:10,469 --> 00:00:11,762
(FOOTSTEPS)

2
00:00:21,689 --> 00:00:23,024
(LIQUID POURING)

3
00:00:25,192 --> 00:00:26,527
-(CLICK)
(WHIRRING)

4
00:00:29,697 --> 00:00:30,698
-(CLICK)
(WHIRRING STOPS)

5
00:00:32,158 --> 00:00:32,742
-(CLATTER)
-(STATIC)

6
00:00:32,742 --> 00:00:33,409
-(CLATTER)
-(STATIC)

7
00:00:34,577 --> 00:00:36,203
VALERY: (OVER TAPE)
What is the cost of lies?

8
00:00:38,247 --> 00:00:40,291
It's not that we'll mistake them
for the truth.

9
00:00:41,167 --> 00:00:44,003
The real danger is that
if we hear enough lies,

10
00:00:45,004 --> 00:00:47,715
then we no longer recognize
the truth at all.

11
00:00:49,425 --> 00:00:50,718
What can we do then?

12
00:00:51,427 --> 00:00:54,305
What else is left but to abandon
even the hope of truth

13
00:00:54,388 --> 00:00:58,100
and content ourselves instead
with stories?

14
00:00:59,060 --> 00:01:02,104
In these stories,
it doesn't matter who the heroes are.

15
00:01:02,855 --> 00:01:05,149
All we want to know is,
who is to blame?

16
00:01:06,400 --> 00:01:10,488
In this story, it was Anatoly Dyatlov.
He was the best choice.

17
00:01:11,155 --> 00:01:14,283
An arrogant, unpleasant man,
he ran the room that night.

18
00:01:14,367 --> 00:01:15,660
He gave the orders.

19
00:01:16,327 --> 00:01:17,411
And no friends.

20
00:01:18,454 --> 00:01:21,207
Or, at least, not important ones.

21
00:01:23,626 --> 00:01:28,297
And now, Dyatlov will spend the next
10 years in a prison labor camp.

22
00:01:29,548 --> 00:01:32,176
Of course, that sentence
is doubly unfair.

23
00:01:34,470 --> 00:01:37,139
There were far greater criminals
than him at work.

24
00:01:37,807 --> 00:01:39,809
(SIGHS)

25
00:01:39,892 --> 00:01:42,019
And as for what Dyatlov did do...

26
00:01:42,687 --> 00:01:44,605
The man doesn't deserve prison.

27
00:01:46,399 --> 00:01:47,733
He deserves death.

28
00:01:51,988 --> 00:01:52,989
(CLEARS THROAT)

29
00:02:00,997 --> 00:02:02,039
(INHALES)

30
00:02:02,123 --> 00:02:05,543
But instead, ten years
for "criminal mismanagement."

31
00:02:07,003 --> 00:02:08,045
What does that mean?

32
00:02:09,130 --> 00:02:10,214
No one knows.

33
00:02:11,173 --> 00:02:12,299
It doesn't matter.

34
00:02:15,011 --> 00:02:16,721
What does matter is that, to them,

35
00:02:18,556 --> 00:02:20,016
justice was done.

36
00:02:20,933 --> 00:02:23,644
Because, you see, to them,

37
00:02:24,562 --> 00:02:27,565
a just world is a sane world.

38
00:02:28,774 --> 00:02:29,775
(EXHALES)

39
00:02:30,776 --> 00:02:33,112
There was nothing sane
about Chernobyl.

40
00:02:35,573 --> 00:02:37,324
What happened there,
what happened after,

41
00:02:37,700 --> 00:02:40,828
even the good we did, all of it...

42
00:02:42,580 --> 00:02:43,581
All of it...

43
00:02:45,416 --> 00:02:46,417
Madness.

44
00:02:51,088 --> 00:02:54,884
(SIGHS) Well, I've given you
everything I know.

45
00:02:57,553 --> 00:02:59,221
They'll deny it, of course.

46
00:03:00,014 --> 00:03:01,140
They always do.

47
00:03:07,271 --> 00:03:08,564
I know you'll try your best.

48
00:03:16,864 --> 00:03:17,865
(CLICKS)

49
00:03:18,699 --> 00:03:19,700
(WHIRRING)

50
00:03:25,331 --> 00:03:26,332
-(CLICKS)
(WHIRRING STOPS)

51
00:05:05,306 --> 00:05:06,307
(EXHALES)

52
00:05:13,314 --> 00:05:14,315
(DOOR OPENS)

53
00:05:16,066 --> 00:05:17,067
(DOOR CLOSES)

54
00:05:37,880 --> 00:05:38,881
(INHALES DEEPLY)

55
00:05:39,840 --> 00:05:41,175
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

56
00:05:55,564 --> 00:05:56,857
(CLATTERING)

57
00:06:02,696 --> 00:06:04,281
(LOUD CLATTERING)

58
00:06:34,728 --> 00:06:36,063
(VOMITING)

59
00:06:36,981 --> 00:06:38,023
(COUGHS)

60
00:06:39,149 --> 00:06:40,442
(GROANS)

61
00:06:44,655 --> 00:06:46,156
(TOILET FLUSHING)

62
00:06:55,874 --> 00:06:57,209
(SNORING)

63
00:07:19,982 --> 00:07:21,358
(CLATTERING)

64
00:07:29,074 --> 00:07:30,492
-(EXPLOSION)
-(GASPS)

65
00:07:32,953 --> 00:07:33,954
VASILY: Lyudmilla?

66
00:07:34,246 --> 00:07:35,748
(DOGS BARKING)

67
00:07:59,396 --> 00:08:00,689
MAN: Comrade Dyatlov!

68
00:08:05,277 --> 00:08:08,781
Comrade Dyatlov! Comrade Dyatlov!

69
00:08:13,702 --> 00:08:16,538
-Comrade Dyatlov! Comrade Dyatlov!
-(ALARM BLARING)

70
00:08:17,539 --> 00:08:18,624
What just happened?

71
00:08:19,458 --> 00:08:20,459
I don't know.

72
00:08:22,503 --> 00:08:23,629
There's a fire in the turbine hall.

73
00:08:26,215 --> 00:08:27,549
The turbine hall?

74
00:08:28,842 --> 00:08:30,969
The control system tank. Hydrogen.

75
00:08:31,970 --> 00:08:33,847
You and Toptunov,
you morons blew the tank.

76
00:08:34,264 --> 00:08:36,100
-No, that's not...
-This is an emergency.

77
00:08:36,183 --> 00:08:38,227
Everyone stay calm.
Our first priority is...

78
00:08:38,310 --> 00:08:39,353
-It's exploded!
-DYATLOV: We know.

79
00:08:39,728 --> 00:08:41,188
Akimov, are we cooling
the reactor core?

80
00:08:41,271 --> 00:08:43,023
We shut it down,
but the control rods are still active.

81
00:08:43,690 --> 00:08:45,025
They're not all the way in.
I disengaged...

82
00:08:45,109 --> 00:08:47,694
All right. Try and disconnect
the servos from the standby console.

83
00:08:47,903 --> 00:08:49,154
You two, get the backup pumps running.

84
00:08:49,238 --> 00:08:51,031
We need water moving through the core.

85
00:08:51,115 --> 00:08:53,117
-That is all that matters.
-There is no core.

86
00:08:54,493 --> 00:08:56,161
It exploded! The core exploded.

87
00:08:59,957 --> 00:09:01,792
He's in shock. Get him out of here.

88
00:09:02,167 --> 00:09:03,293
The lid is off.

89
00:09:03,502 --> 00:09:05,379
The stack is burning. I saw it.

90
00:09:05,462 --> 00:09:08,257
You're confused.
RBMK reactor cores don't explode.

91
00:09:08,340 --> 00:09:09,716
-Akimov...
-Sasha.

92
00:09:09,800 --> 00:09:13,011
Don't worry, we did everything right.
Something strange has happened.

93
00:09:13,095 --> 00:09:14,388
-Do you taste metal?
-Akimov!

94
00:09:15,764 --> 00:09:18,225
Comrade Perevozchenko, what you're
saying is physically impossible.

95
00:09:18,308 --> 00:09:21,019
The core can't explode.
It has to be the tank.

96
00:09:22,729 --> 00:09:24,106
We're wasting time. Let's go.

97
00:09:24,481 --> 00:09:26,859
Get the hydrogen out of the generators
and pump water into the core.

98
00:09:27,359 --> 00:09:28,569
What about the fire?

99
00:09:29,486 --> 00:09:30,696
Call the fire brigade.

100
00:09:30,863 --> 00:09:32,531
(ALARM CONTINUES BLARING)

101
00:09:43,542 --> 00:09:45,544
(ALARM CONTINUES BLARING)

102
00:10:13,739 --> 00:10:15,032
(GLASS CRUNCHING)

103
00:10:31,548 --> 00:10:33,133
(BEEPS)

104
00:10:33,300 --> 00:10:35,302
-Is this Military Fire Station 2?
-Yes.

105
00:10:35,719 --> 00:10:37,095
What's happening with the accident?

106
00:10:37,179 --> 00:10:40,974
Explosion in the main building
between the third and fourth blocks.

107
00:10:42,476 --> 00:10:44,394
-Are there people there?
-Yes.

108
00:10:44,645 --> 00:10:45,979
Wake up the bosses. Call them.

109
00:10:46,855 --> 00:10:48,774
I already called mine.

110
00:10:48,857 --> 00:10:53,195
Wake them up, wake them up.
Wake up the entire officers' block.

111
00:10:53,278 --> 00:10:55,072
(BEEPS)

112
00:10:55,239 --> 00:10:57,241
-Fire department.
-Hello, Lvankov?

113
00:10:57,366 --> 00:11:00,160
-Yes. Yes?
-You've been called to Pripyat.

114
00:11:00,327 --> 00:11:02,037
-Hello?
-Yes. Yes I can hear you.

115
00:11:02,120 --> 00:11:05,707
At the nuclear plant over there,
in the third and fourth blocks.

116
00:11:05,791 --> 00:11:06,833
The roof is on fire.

117
00:11:07,709 --> 00:11:09,253
(IN ENGLISH)
You're not on call tonight.

118
00:11:09,336 --> 00:11:11,338
VASILY: They're bringing everybody in,
military and civil.

119
00:11:12,047 --> 00:11:14,925
Pripyat, Polesskoe, Kiev.

120
00:11:15,801 --> 00:11:16,802
This is a big one.

121
00:11:18,387 --> 00:11:21,223
But it doesn't look right, the color.

122
00:11:21,515 --> 00:11:24,643
PRAVIK says he thinks they're shining
floodlights or something.

123
00:11:24,726 --> 00:11:26,103
And what if there are chemicals?

124
00:11:26,895 --> 00:11:28,313
(CHUCKLING) "Chemicals"?

125
00:11:29,481 --> 00:11:30,691
The problem's the roof.

126
00:11:31,191 --> 00:11:32,234
It's covered in tar,

127
00:11:32,317 --> 00:11:35,153
so it's gonna burn all night,
and it'll stink like hell.

128
00:11:35,654 --> 00:11:38,031
That's it. That's the worst of it.

129
00:11:40,659 --> 00:11:41,660
Go back to bed.

130
00:11:41,827 --> 00:11:42,828
(DOOR OPENS)

131
00:11:44,788 --> 00:11:45,789
(DOOR CLOSES)

132
00:11:48,375 --> 00:11:50,210
(ALARM BLARING)

133
00:12:09,229 --> 00:12:11,315
(CREAKING)

134
00:12:17,654 --> 00:12:19,906
-MAN: Is it war?
-Where's the dosimeter?

135
00:12:20,657 --> 00:12:23,035
MAN: Here. Here.

136
00:12:26,288 --> 00:12:27,372
(RUMBLING)

137
00:12:29,750 --> 00:12:31,168
Are they bombing?

138
00:12:34,379 --> 00:12:36,965
What the fuck is this?
It's 3.6 roentgen.

139
00:12:37,049 --> 00:12:39,509
That's as high as it goes.
The good one's locked in a safe.

140
00:12:39,593 --> 00:12:40,927
I don't have a key.

141
00:12:41,595 --> 00:12:44,890
Valera... Your face.

142
00:12:47,100 --> 00:12:48,101
Come on.

143
00:12:48,810 --> 00:12:51,063
I'm going to find Khodemchuk
in the pump room.

144
00:12:51,146 --> 00:12:52,648
You, here.

145
00:12:53,273 --> 00:12:56,652
Get Shashenok. He's in 604. Go.

146
00:12:57,069 --> 00:12:58,487
We need to get everyone out!

147
00:12:58,737 --> 00:13:00,238
(ALARM CONTINUES BLARING)

148
00:13:08,789 --> 00:13:09,790
(COUGHING)

149
00:13:10,290 --> 00:13:11,708
-(GASPING)
-(VOMITING)

150
00:13:12,376 --> 00:13:13,377
Shit.

151
00:13:13,460 --> 00:13:15,754
Hey! We need to get
to the reactor hall.

152
00:13:15,837 --> 00:13:18,757
-The lift's destroyed.
-Up two flights and across.

153
00:13:19,216 --> 00:13:21,677
-Right.
-Why are you going there?

154
00:13:36,650 --> 00:13:37,734
(THUDDING)

155
00:13:38,276 --> 00:13:39,403
(GRUNTING)

156
00:13:41,822 --> 00:13:43,031
Have you seen Khodemchuk?

157
00:13:43,657 --> 00:13:45,951
-No. Where's Viktor?
-Still in the pump room.

158
00:13:47,661 --> 00:13:48,662
-(VOMITS)
-(GASPS)

159
00:13:49,121 --> 00:13:50,288
Stay here. I'll come back.

160
00:13:53,291 --> 00:13:54,668
Viktor!

161
00:14:12,686 --> 00:14:14,229
-(VIKTOR COUGHING)
-Viktor.

162
00:14:15,814 --> 00:14:16,815
Viktor.

163
00:14:17,607 --> 00:14:18,608
Oh!

164
00:14:18,859 --> 00:14:21,194
Viktor, I'm gonna get you out of here.

165
00:14:21,862 --> 00:14:23,613
-Can you stand?
-(COUGHING)

166
00:14:24,573 --> 00:14:25,741
(GASPS) Khodemchuk...

167
00:14:25,824 --> 00:14:26,908
Where?

168
00:14:29,953 --> 00:14:31,329
Get Khodemchuk.

169
00:14:54,936 --> 00:14:55,937
(GASPING)

170
00:15:00,233 --> 00:15:02,235
(ALARM BLARING IN DISTANCE)

171
00:15:13,914 --> 00:15:14,915
(ALARM BLARING)

172
00:15:15,373 --> 00:15:17,292
I dropped the control rods
from the other panel.

173
00:15:17,375 --> 00:15:19,169
-AKIMOV: They're still up.
-What?

174
00:15:19,252 --> 00:15:21,379
They're still only a third
of the way in. I don't know why.

175
00:15:21,838 --> 00:15:22,881
I already sent the trainees down

176
00:15:22,964 --> 00:15:24,299
to the reactor hall
to lower them by hand.

177
00:15:24,382 --> 00:15:26,301
-What about the pumps?
-I can't get through to Khodemchuk.

178
00:15:26,384 --> 00:15:28,929
-The lines are down.
-Fuck the phones and fuck Khodemchuk.

179
00:15:29,095 --> 00:15:30,597
-Are the pumps on or not?
-Stolyarchuk?

180
00:15:30,680 --> 00:15:33,475
My control panel's not working.
I tried calling for the electricians.

181
00:15:33,558 --> 00:15:37,270
I don't give a shit about the panel!
I need water in my reactor core!

182
00:15:38,313 --> 00:15:40,190
Get down there
and make sure those pumps are on.

183
00:15:41,525 --> 00:15:42,526
Now!

184
00:15:50,033 --> 00:15:51,785
-(DOOR OPENS)
-What does the dosimeter say?

185
00:15:51,993 --> 00:15:54,246
Uh, 3.6 roentgen, but that's as high
as the meter...

186
00:15:54,329 --> 00:15:56,581
Three point six.
Not great, not terrible.

187
00:16:05,173 --> 00:16:06,383
We did everything right.

188
00:16:10,887 --> 00:16:12,889
(SIRENS WAILING)

189
00:16:33,118 --> 00:16:35,161
(INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER)

190
00:16:43,461 --> 00:16:44,963
(MEN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

191
00:16:51,553 --> 00:16:53,138
FIREMAN 1: You, connect those hooks!

192
00:16:59,269 --> 00:17:00,270
FIREMAN 2: Get the pumps going!

193
00:17:00,353 --> 00:17:02,480
FIREMAN 3: Yeah, over here!
I'm right with you!

194
00:17:06,526 --> 00:17:09,237
FIREMAN 1: We're working
bottom to top. Go in fast.

195
00:17:10,447 --> 00:17:12,198
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

196
00:17:30,216 --> 00:17:31,217
MISHA: VASILY...

197
00:17:33,386 --> 00:17:36,014
-Hey, VASILY, what's this?
- I don't know, Misha.

198
00:17:36,097 --> 00:17:38,224
Don't fuck around with it.
Hook these up. Come on.

199
00:17:44,439 --> 00:17:45,440
Do you taste metal?

200
00:17:45,941 --> 00:17:48,652
-Yeah, what is that?
-I don't know.

201
00:17:50,695 --> 00:17:52,113
The valves, Misha.
The valves! Let's go.

202
00:17:52,322 --> 00:17:53,657
The valves! Come on!

203
00:18:02,165 --> 00:18:03,541
(SIREN WAILING)

204
00:18:08,964 --> 00:18:10,966
(ALARM BLARING)

205
00:18:26,147 --> 00:18:27,148
What do you need?

206
00:18:28,191 --> 00:18:29,859
We need to get into the reactor hall

207
00:18:29,943 --> 00:18:31,861
to lower the control rods,
but the door's jammed.

208
00:18:33,905 --> 00:18:35,490
I don't think there are control rods.

209
00:18:35,782 --> 00:18:36,950
I don't think there's a core.

210
00:18:39,244 --> 00:18:40,870
No, you're... You're mistaken.

211
00:18:42,080 --> 00:18:43,081
Akimov said.

212
00:18:58,388 --> 00:18:59,389
(PANTING)

213
00:19:00,640 --> 00:19:01,641
Let's go.

214
00:19:15,363 --> 00:19:16,906
FIREMAN 1: (SHOUTING) No!

215
00:19:17,282 --> 00:19:18,283
(FIREMAN 1 SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

216
00:19:18,658 --> 00:19:20,618
Ignatenko, get on his hose!

217
00:19:21,327 --> 00:19:22,579
FIREMAN 2: It's all right. Breathe.

218
00:19:22,912 --> 00:19:23,913
-Misha.
-(MISHA GROANING)

219
00:19:24,581 --> 00:19:26,166
FIREMAN 2: All right, all right.
Easy, Misha.

220
00:19:27,375 --> 00:19:28,710
(MISHA CONTINUES GROANING
AND SCREAMING)

221
00:20:03,411 --> 00:20:04,412
Are you sure?

222
00:20:06,581 --> 00:20:07,582
Akimov...

223
00:20:12,212 --> 00:20:13,213
(BOTH GRUNTING)

224
00:20:21,554 --> 00:20:22,555
Move.

225
00:20:29,979 --> 00:20:31,397
(GRUNTING)

226
00:20:33,066 --> 00:20:34,442
Come on! Go! Go!

227
00:20:37,028 --> 00:20:38,029
(PEREVOZSCHENKO GRUNTS)

228
00:20:38,279 --> 00:20:39,572
Go! Go fast, go!

229
00:20:45,829 --> 00:20:47,080
(DOOR CREAKING)

230
00:21:12,063 --> 00:21:13,064
(GRUNTS)

231
00:21:13,356 --> 00:21:14,357
Let's go!

232
00:21:15,567 --> 00:21:16,568
Let's go!

233
00:21:18,319 --> 00:21:20,029
Hey! (GROANS)

234
00:21:24,200 --> 00:21:25,201
(GROANING)

235
00:21:26,661 --> 00:21:27,662
Hey!

236
00:21:41,426 --> 00:21:43,052
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-(SIRENS WAILING)

237
00:21:48,183 --> 00:21:50,310
OKSANA: Lyudmilla! Do you want
to come with us?

238
00:21:50,852 --> 00:21:51,853
Come where?

239
00:21:51,978 --> 00:21:53,771
We're going to the railroad bridge
to get a better look.

240
00:21:54,230 --> 00:21:56,566
It's not like anyone
can sleep with all the sirens.

241
00:21:56,816 --> 00:21:58,860
I don't think you should go.
It could be dangerous.

242
00:21:58,943 --> 00:21:59,944
MIKHAIL: What do you mean,
"dangerous"?

243
00:22:00,403 --> 00:22:01,905
It's a fire.
It's over there, we're over here.

244
00:22:01,988 --> 00:22:03,573
-Mikhail.
-What?

245
00:22:05,116 --> 00:22:07,160
Oh. Sorry.

246
00:22:12,165 --> 00:22:13,625
-Is VASILY...
-Yeah.

247
00:22:14,459 --> 00:22:15,835
Did he say it was bad?

248
00:22:15,919 --> 00:22:17,795
No. No, he said it was just the roof.

249
00:22:17,879 --> 00:22:20,256
Well, he's never gotten hurt before.
None of the boys have.

250
00:22:21,925 --> 00:22:22,926
He'll be fine.

251
00:22:24,677 --> 00:22:25,678
Get some rest.

252
00:22:38,650 --> 00:22:39,943
DYATLOV: The tank, it's big enough.

253
00:22:40,026 --> 00:22:42,820
This kind of explosion,
the control tank on 71,

254
00:22:42,904 --> 00:22:44,155
it's 100 cubic meters.

255
00:22:44,239 --> 00:22:45,657
One hundred and ten.

256
00:22:45,823 --> 00:22:49,244
Hundred and ten.
It could do this, definitely.

257
00:22:49,786 --> 00:22:50,828
(PANTING) It's gone.

258
00:22:51,955 --> 00:22:53,206
I looked right into it.

259
00:22:54,082 --> 00:22:55,625
I looked into the core.

260
00:22:56,918 --> 00:22:58,753
Did you lower the control rods or not?

261
00:23:00,004 --> 00:23:01,214
(RETCHING)

262
00:23:02,215 --> 00:23:03,549
Take him to the infirmary.

263
00:23:06,135 --> 00:23:07,720
Toptunov, take him!

264
00:23:11,266 --> 00:23:12,684
Where's Kudryavstev?

265
00:23:13,601 --> 00:23:14,727
He fell.

266
00:23:15,103 --> 00:23:17,689
-TOPTUNOV: I need a medic! Anyone!
-He's delusional.

267
00:23:18,856 --> 00:23:20,608
-His face...
-Ruptured condenser lines.

268
00:23:20,692 --> 00:23:23,820
The feed water is mildly contaminated.
He'll be fine. I've seen worse.

269
00:23:24,487 --> 00:23:26,698
Do we still have
a phone line to the outside?

270
00:23:28,616 --> 00:23:30,285
-Akimov?
-(GASPS)

271
00:23:31,703 --> 00:23:33,037
DYATLOV: Call in the day shift.

272
00:23:34,455 --> 00:23:35,498
But if the...

273
00:23:35,581 --> 00:23:37,333
We have to keep water flowing
into the core.

274
00:23:37,417 --> 00:23:40,253
We need electricians,
mechanics, we need bodies.

275
00:23:41,212 --> 00:23:43,089
How many times do I have to say it?

276
00:23:51,848 --> 00:23:53,975
I'm going to
the Administration Building now

277
00:23:54,058 --> 00:23:55,935
to call Bryukhanov and Fomin.

278
00:23:56,686 --> 00:23:57,895
They're gonna want a full report.

279
00:24:00,148 --> 00:24:02,692
Now, I don't know if I can
make things better for you...

280
00:24:03,985 --> 00:24:05,611
But I can certainly make them worse.

281
00:24:08,823 --> 00:24:11,075
Call in the day shift, Comrade Akimov.

282
00:24:14,871 --> 00:24:16,205
Yes, Comrade Dyatlov.

283
00:24:25,715 --> 00:24:26,716
(INHALES AND EXHALES SHARPLY)

284
00:24:29,969 --> 00:24:30,970
(DOOR CLOSES)

285
00:24:49,864 --> 00:24:50,865
DOCTOR: You're doing fine.

286
00:24:52,283 --> 00:24:53,284
Raise her up.

287
00:24:57,538 --> 00:25:00,500
That one, maybe an hour.
This one, not until morning.

288
00:25:03,461 --> 00:25:05,004
How's it downstairs, Doctor?

289
00:25:05,671 --> 00:25:06,672
DR. ZINCHENKO: Quiet.

290
00:25:07,465 --> 00:25:08,591
Always is.

291
00:25:09,300 --> 00:25:11,302
Nothing at this hour but babies.

292
00:25:12,929 --> 00:25:15,306
Do you know I once went
two days without sleep?

293
00:25:15,932 --> 00:25:18,267
Ten women went into labor
at the same time.

294
00:25:18,601 --> 00:25:20,770
-Did I ever tell you that story?
-Yes.

295
00:25:23,064 --> 00:25:24,982
Well, I won't need you
in here for a while.

296
00:25:25,066 --> 00:25:27,485
If you want,
get some rest in the break room.

297
00:25:28,569 --> 00:25:30,405
They haven't brought
anyone in from the fire.

298
00:25:30,905 --> 00:25:31,948
What fire?

299
00:25:32,281 --> 00:25:33,533
The power plant.

300
00:25:34,951 --> 00:25:37,453
DOCTOR: Oh.
Well, then it mustn't be too bad.

301
00:25:38,704 --> 00:25:39,997
DR. ZINCHENKO: Do we stock iodine?

302
00:25:40,540 --> 00:25:42,458
-Hmm?
-iodine.

303
00:25:43,918 --> 00:25:45,336
You mean disinfectant?

304
00:25:45,420 --> 00:25:48,005
No, pills. Does the hospital
stock iodine pills?

305
00:25:48,089 --> 00:25:50,758
Iodine pills?
Why would we have iodine pills?

306
00:25:51,509 --> 00:25:52,718
(PHONE RINGING)

307
00:25:56,556 --> 00:25:57,765
(CONTINUES RINGING)

308
00:26:03,479 --> 00:26:04,856
Hello? (COUGHING)

309
00:26:06,399 --> 00:26:07,400
Hello?

310
00:26:08,943 --> 00:26:10,528
-(INDISTINCT TALKING ON PHONE)
(GRUNTS)

311
00:26:14,949 --> 00:26:16,367
Who else knows this?

312
00:26:18,870 --> 00:26:19,871
Have you called Fomin?

313
00:26:21,664 --> 00:26:25,835
Of course, I want you to call him.
If I'm up, he's up.

314
00:26:46,898 --> 00:26:48,858
(SIREN WAILING)

315
00:27:04,373 --> 00:27:07,627
Whatever the cause, the important
thing is that neither you nor I...

316
00:27:21,140 --> 00:27:22,141
(DOOR CLOSES)

317
00:27:43,746 --> 00:27:44,997
(DOOR LOCKING)

318
00:27:49,252 --> 00:27:51,254
I take it the safety test
was a failure.

319
00:27:51,671 --> 00:27:54,298
-We have the situation under control.
-FOMIN: "Under control"?

320
00:27:54,799 --> 00:27:56,133
It doesn't look
like it's under control.

321
00:27:56,217 --> 00:27:57,218
Shut up, Fomin.

322
00:27:58,803 --> 00:28:01,472
I have to tell the Central Committee
about this. Do you realize that?

323
00:28:01,931 --> 00:28:03,599
I have to get on the phone
and tell Mar yin,

324
00:28:03,683 --> 00:28:07,144
or, God forbid, Frolyshev,
that my power plant is on fire.

325
00:28:07,228 --> 00:28:09,647
No one can blame you for this,
Director Bryukhanov.

326
00:28:09,730 --> 00:28:11,148
Of course no one can
blame me for this.

327
00:28:11,232 --> 00:28:14,360
How can I be responsible?
I was sleeping.

328
00:28:15,403 --> 00:28:17,321
Tell me what happened, quickly.

329
00:28:19,282 --> 00:28:22,451
We ran the test exactly as
Chief Engineer Fomin approved.

330
00:28:22,994 --> 00:28:25,705
Unit Shift Chief Akimov
and Engineer Toptunov

331
00:28:25,997 --> 00:28:27,623
encountered technical difficulties,

332
00:28:27,707 --> 00:28:30,960
leading to an accumulation of hydrogen
in the control system tank.

333
00:28:31,877 --> 00:28:33,337
It regrettably ignited,

334
00:28:33,421 --> 00:28:35,548
damaging the plant,
setting the roof on fire.

335
00:28:38,092 --> 00:28:39,468
The tank is quite large.

336
00:28:40,219 --> 00:28:41,846
It's the only logical explanation.

337
00:28:42,430 --> 00:28:45,725
Of course,
Deputy Chief Engineer Dyatlov

338
00:28:45,808 --> 00:28:49,729
was directly supervising the test,
so he would know best.

339
00:28:49,812 --> 00:28:51,689
BRYUKHANOV: A hydrogen tank, fire...

340
00:28:54,567 --> 00:28:56,360
-Reactor?
-We're taking measures to ensure

341
00:28:56,652 --> 00:28:58,404
a steady flow of water
through the core.

342
00:28:59,322 --> 00:29:02,116
-What about radiation?
-Obviously, down here it's nothing,

343
00:29:02,199 --> 00:29:06,287
but in the reactor building,
I'm being told, 3.6 roentgen per hour.

344
00:29:07,204 --> 00:29:08,914
Well, that's not great,
but it's not horrifying.

345
00:29:08,998 --> 00:29:09,999
FOMIN: Not at all.

346
00:29:10,750 --> 00:29:12,460
From the feed water, I assume.

347
00:29:12,543 --> 00:29:13,544
Mmm-hmm.

348
00:29:15,296 --> 00:29:18,299
We'll have to limit shifts to
six hours at a time, but otherwise...

349
00:29:18,633 --> 00:29:20,968
The dosimetrists
should be checking regularly.

350
00:29:22,094 --> 00:29:25,139
Have them use
the good meter from the safe.

351
00:29:26,474 --> 00:29:27,475
(GROANS) Right.

352
00:29:28,517 --> 00:29:29,935
I'll call Mar yin.

353
00:29:31,145 --> 00:29:33,564
Have them wake up the local
Executive Committee.

354
00:29:33,648 --> 00:29:35,024
There'll be orders coming down.

355
00:29:35,650 --> 00:29:36,901
(PEOPLE TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

356
00:29:41,238 --> 00:29:42,239
OKSANA: Here.

357
00:29:42,782 --> 00:29:45,326
Sure? Okay.

358
00:29:48,663 --> 00:29:50,122
What do you think makes the colors?

359
00:29:50,206 --> 00:29:51,207
Oh.

360
00:29:51,874 --> 00:29:55,044
-It's the fuel, for sure.
-"It's the fuel, for sure."

361
00:29:55,419 --> 00:29:58,464
What do you know about it?
You clean floors at a train station.

362
00:29:58,839 --> 00:30:00,549
My friend, Yuri,
works at the power plant.

363
00:30:00,633 --> 00:30:01,759
He says it runs cold.

364
00:30:02,301 --> 00:30:04,011
No gas, no fire. Just atoms.

365
00:30:05,054 --> 00:30:07,264
Yuri says the only thing is,
you can't walk right up to the fuel.

366
00:30:07,682 --> 00:30:10,393
If you do, a glass of vodka
an hour for four hours.

367
00:30:11,185 --> 00:30:12,812
Isn't Yuri a plumber?

368
00:30:13,479 --> 00:30:15,606
At the nuclear power plant, yeah.

369
00:30:15,981 --> 00:30:17,066
(CHUCKLES)

370
00:30:22,154 --> 00:30:23,572
Well, it is beautiful.

371
00:30:24,949 --> 00:30:25,950
Yeah.

372
00:31:18,002 --> 00:31:19,587
(INAUDIBLE)

373
00:31:37,480 --> 00:31:39,482
(ALARM BLARING)

374
00:31:42,651 --> 00:31:44,153
(COUGHING)

375
00:32:17,895 --> 00:32:19,313
Do you have a cigarette?

376
00:32:45,297 --> 00:32:46,507
Do you need help?

377
00:32:53,472 --> 00:32:54,473
It's over.

378
00:33:11,490 --> 00:33:12,825
(SHUDDERING)

379
00:33:47,818 --> 00:33:49,153
(MAN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

380
00:33:59,830 --> 00:34:01,498
We've done all we can
from the perimeter.

381
00:34:01,582 --> 00:34:03,250
We need to start making
our way to the roof.

382
00:34:10,424 --> 00:34:11,425
FIREMAN 1: VASILY!

383
00:34:12,092 --> 00:34:13,135
You've gotta put it out.

384
00:34:17,181 --> 00:34:19,975
FIREMAN 2: That's enough, comrades.
We're pushing ahead.

385
00:34:25,856 --> 00:34:26,857
Come on, boys.

386
00:34:33,447 --> 00:34:35,032
FIREMAN: VASILY,
it's just past, straight up.

387
00:34:35,491 --> 00:34:37,076
All the way up, all the way in.

388
00:34:39,161 --> 00:34:40,162
Come on!

389
00:34:52,925 --> 00:34:54,593
Yeah. Going in now.

390
00:35:00,099 --> 00:35:01,266
(VASILY BREATHING HEAVILY)

391
00:35:42,599 --> 00:35:43,767
What about the auxiliary?

392
00:35:44,768 --> 00:35:47,563
The pumps are gone, electrical's gone.

393
00:35:48,605 --> 00:35:49,606
The core?

394
00:35:50,065 --> 00:35:52,026
I didn't go in there, and I won't.

395
00:35:54,194 --> 00:35:55,237
I think it's time we faced...

396
00:35:55,362 --> 00:35:56,613
No, we have to get water into
the core.

397
00:35:56,697 --> 00:35:57,781
Otherwise, there'll be a meltdown.

398
00:35:58,866 --> 00:36:00,284
We have to open the valves.

399
00:36:00,367 --> 00:36:02,369
-Sasha...
-What do you want, Boris?

400
00:36:02,453 --> 00:36:04,455
If it's true, then we're dead.
A million people are dead.

401
00:36:04,705 --> 00:36:05,831
Is that what you need to hear?

402
00:36:08,292 --> 00:36:09,877
We have to open the valves.

403
00:36:10,169 --> 00:36:11,462
-By hand.
-STOLYARCHUK: By hand?

404
00:36:13,255 --> 00:36:14,965
The number of valves,
the amount of time to turn them,

405
00:36:15,049 --> 00:36:16,675
you're talking about hours in there!

406
00:36:16,759 --> 00:36:18,343
-Then help us.
-Help you do what?

407
00:36:18,802 --> 00:36:21,180
Pump water into a ditch?
There's nothing there!

408
00:36:31,065 --> 00:36:32,274
Leonid, I'm begging you.

409
00:36:46,121 --> 00:36:47,372
Watch the panel while we're gone.

410
00:36:47,915 --> 00:36:49,041
It's not working.

411
00:36:50,334 --> 00:36:51,335
Just watch it.

412
00:36:56,965 --> 00:36:57,966
(DOOR CLOSES)

413
00:37:09,561 --> 00:37:10,562
(SOBS)

414
00:37:14,108 --> 00:37:15,818
MAN: I guess we know why
they called us in early.

415
00:37:16,276 --> 00:37:17,820
SITNIKOV: Is anyone
saying what happened?

416
00:37:18,487 --> 00:37:20,572
MAN: They were running
the safety test on the turbines,

417
00:37:20,948 --> 00:37:22,699
blew the control system tank.

418
00:37:24,076 --> 00:37:25,202
It doesn't make sense to me either.

419
00:37:27,246 --> 00:37:28,330
SITNIKOV: What about sabotage?

420
00:37:29,456 --> 00:37:30,457
A bomb?

421
00:37:31,708 --> 00:37:32,751
SITNIKOV!

422
00:37:33,293 --> 00:37:35,546
Bryukhanov wants us to use
the good dosimeter,

423
00:37:35,629 --> 00:37:38,340
but it's in the safe,
and we can't find the key.

424
00:37:38,423 --> 00:37:40,384
It's in Building Two. Hasn't...

425
00:37:41,760 --> 00:37:42,803
Follow me.

426
00:37:45,389 --> 00:37:46,390
(DOOR OPENS)

427
00:37:54,690 --> 00:37:55,983
Gentlemen, welcome.

428
00:37:56,358 --> 00:37:59,611
Please, uh, find a seat.
Plenty of room.

429
00:38:00,487 --> 00:38:02,447
I apologize for the lateness
of the hour.

430
00:38:03,282 --> 00:38:06,910
Rest assured,
we are all very safe down here.

431
00:38:07,369 --> 00:38:10,205
We built this shelter
to withstand a nuclear attack

432
00:38:10,289 --> 00:38:13,167
by the Americans,
so, I think we'll be fine.

433
00:38:15,127 --> 00:38:17,588
Um, as you can see,
we have experienced an accident.

434
00:38:17,671 --> 00:38:20,299
A large control tank malfunctioned,

435
00:38:20,382 --> 00:38:24,303
damaging reactor Building Four
and starting a fire.

436
00:38:24,386 --> 00:38:27,931
Now, I have spoken directly
to Deputy Secretary Mar yin.

437
00:38:28,015 --> 00:38:30,142
Mar yin spoke
to Deputy Chief Frolyshev,

438
00:38:30,434 --> 00:38:33,270
Frolyshev to Central Committee
member Dolgikh,

439
00:38:33,687 --> 00:38:36,857
and Dolgikh to
General Secretary Gorbachev.

440
00:38:37,441 --> 00:38:38,442
Now...

441
00:38:40,110 --> 00:38:44,364
Because the Central Committee
has the greatest respect

442
00:38:44,448 --> 00:38:47,993
for the work of the Pripyat
Executive Committee,

443
00:38:48,368 --> 00:38:51,872
they have asked me to brief you
on matters as they stand, so...

444
00:38:53,874 --> 00:38:55,417
First, the accident...

445
00:38:55,500 --> 00:38:57,461
(STUTTERING) It's well under control.

446
00:38:58,170 --> 00:39:03,050
And second, because the efforts
of the Soviet nuclear industry

447
00:39:03,133 --> 00:39:06,511
are considered key State secrets,
it is important

448
00:39:06,845 --> 00:39:12,142
that we ensure that this incident
has no adverse consequences.

449
00:39:12,601 --> 00:39:14,144
Now, to prevent a panic,

450
00:39:14,895 --> 00:39:16,563
the Central Committee have ordered

451
00:39:16,647 --> 00:39:19,233
a detachment of military police
to Pripyat.

452
00:39:19,524 --> 00:39:20,901
How large of a detachment?

453
00:39:22,694 --> 00:39:24,488
Between 2,000 and 4,000 men.

454
00:39:27,074 --> 00:39:28,492
PETROVICH:
What's really going on here?

455
00:39:29,368 --> 00:39:30,786
How dangerous is this?

456
00:39:31,495 --> 00:39:34,831
There's mild radiation,
but it's limited to the plant itself.

457
00:39:35,082 --> 00:39:37,000
-PETROVICH: No, it isn't.
-Excuse me?

458
00:39:38,252 --> 00:39:40,796
PETROVICH:
You saw men outside vomiting.

459
00:39:42,214 --> 00:39:43,465
You saw men with burns.

460
00:39:45,050 --> 00:39:46,718
There's more radiation
than they're saying.

461
00:39:47,552 --> 00:39:49,554
We have wives here, we have children.

462
00:39:49,888 --> 00:39:52,266
I say we evacuate the town.

463
00:39:53,225 --> 00:39:54,226
BRYUKHANOV: Gentlemen...

464
00:39:54,559 --> 00:39:57,938
Please... Please! My wife is here.

465
00:39:58,772 --> 00:40:01,984
Do you think I would keep her
in Pripyat if it wasn't safe?

466
00:40:02,359 --> 00:40:05,821
Bryukhanov, the air is glowing.

467
00:40:05,988 --> 00:40:06,989
DYATLOV: The Cherenkov effect.

468
00:40:08,115 --> 00:40:10,993
Completely normal phenomenon.
It can happen with minimal radiation.

469
00:40:12,119 --> 00:40:13,161
(TAPPING)

470
00:40:21,503 --> 00:40:24,840
I wonder how many of you
know the name of this place.

471
00:40:27,801 --> 00:40:30,137
We all call it "Chernobyl," of course.

472
00:40:31,930 --> 00:40:33,557
What is its real name?

473
00:40:34,975 --> 00:40:38,395
The Vladimir I. Lenin
Nuclear Power Station.

474
00:40:39,479 --> 00:40:40,647
Exactly.

475
00:40:42,941 --> 00:40:45,986
Viadimir I. Lenin.

476
00:40:53,744 --> 00:40:56,830
And how proud he would be
of you all tonight.

477
00:40:58,457 --> 00:41:00,459
Especially you, young man,

478
00:41:01,877 --> 00:41:04,129
and the passion you have
for the people.

479
00:41:05,589 --> 00:41:09,134
For is that not the sole purpose
of the apparatus of the State?

480
00:41:11,386 --> 00:41:12,929
Sometimes, we forget.

481
00:41:14,639 --> 00:41:16,600
Sometimes, we fall prey to fear.

482
00:41:19,227 --> 00:41:22,314
But our faith in Soviet socialism

483
00:41:23,315 --> 00:41:25,484
will always be rewarded.

484
00:41:28,445 --> 00:41:32,282
Now, the State tells us
the situation here is not dangerous.

485
00:41:33,158 --> 00:41:34,993
Have faith, comrades.

486
00:41:37,204 --> 00:41:40,165
The State tells us
it wants to prevent a panic.

487
00:41:40,248 --> 00:41:41,625
Listen well.

488
00:41:44,878 --> 00:41:48,840
It's true, when the people see
the police, they will be afraid.

489
00:41:50,384 --> 00:41:52,344
But it is my experience

490
00:41:53,678 --> 00:41:55,847
that when the people ask questions

491
00:41:55,931 --> 00:41:58,100
that are not
in their own best interest...

492
00:41:59,226 --> 00:42:03,355
They should simply be told
to keep their minds on their labor,

493
00:42:04,439 --> 00:42:06,608
and leave matters of the State

494
00:42:07,734 --> 00:42:08,902
to the State.

495
00:42:11,071 --> 00:42:12,656
We seal off the city.

496
00:42:14,157 --> 00:42:15,409
No one leaves.

497
00:42:16,576 --> 00:42:18,161
And cut the phone lines.

498
00:42:18,995 --> 00:42:21,206
Contain the spread of misinformation.

499
00:42:24,418 --> 00:42:27,295
That is how we keep the people

500
00:42:27,379 --> 00:42:30,006
from undermining the fruits
of their own labor.

501
00:42:33,427 --> 00:42:34,678
Yes, comrades.

502
00:42:36,346 --> 00:42:39,891
We will all be rewarded
for what we do here tonight.

503
00:42:42,769 --> 00:42:46,148
This is our moment to shine.

504
00:42:59,244 --> 00:43:00,245
Thank you.

505
00:43:13,383 --> 00:43:15,635
Comrade SITNIKOV to see
the Chief Engineer.

506
00:43:28,899 --> 00:43:29,900
Well?

507
00:43:32,027 --> 00:43:33,069
(CLEARS THROAT)

508
00:43:36,781 --> 00:43:39,826
I sent my dosimetrists
into the reactor building.

509
00:43:41,745 --> 00:43:42,996
The large dosimeter from the safe,

510
00:43:43,079 --> 00:43:44,831
the one with
the 1,000-roentgen capacity...

511
00:43:44,915 --> 00:43:45,916
What was the number?

512
00:43:49,461 --> 00:43:50,712
There was none.

513
00:43:51,087 --> 00:43:53,215
The meter burned out
the second it was turned on.

514
00:43:54,424 --> 00:43:55,425
It's typical.

515
00:43:55,509 --> 00:43:56,593
BRYUKHANOV:
See, this is what Moscow does.

516
00:43:56,676 --> 00:43:59,596
Sends us shit equipment,
then wonders why things go wrong.

517
00:43:59,679 --> 00:44:03,225
We found another dosimeter,
from the military fire department.

518
00:44:04,184 --> 00:44:06,645
It only goes to 200 roentgen,
but it's better than the small ones.

519
00:44:06,728 --> 00:44:07,729
And?

520
00:44:09,064 --> 00:44:10,398
It maxed out.

521
00:44:11,316 --> 00:44:12,484
Two-hundred roentgen.

522
00:44:15,445 --> 00:44:16,863
What game are you playing?

523
00:44:17,364 --> 00:44:18,532
(STUTTERING) No, I...

524
00:44:19,157 --> 00:44:21,243
I asked him.
He took multiple measurements.

525
00:44:21,576 --> 00:44:22,619
He's my best man.

526
00:44:22,953 --> 00:44:25,330
It's another faulty meter.
You're wasting our time.

527
00:44:25,664 --> 00:44:27,457
I checked the meter
against the control.

528
00:44:27,541 --> 00:44:29,751
What's wrong with you?
How'd you get that number

529
00:44:29,834 --> 00:44:31,753
from feed water leaking
from a blown tank?

530
00:44:35,048 --> 00:44:36,049
You don't.

531
00:44:36,675 --> 00:44:38,468
Then what the fuck
are you talking about?

532
00:44:42,973 --> 00:44:43,974
... (CLEARS THROAT)

533
00:44:46,851 --> 00:44:49,604
I walked around the exterior
of Building Four.

534
00:44:51,439 --> 00:44:54,192
I think there's graphite
on the ground in the rubble.

535
00:44:55,610 --> 00:44:56,987
You didn't see graphite.

536
00:44:58,321 --> 00:44:59,531
- I did.
-You didn't.

537
00:45:01,241 --> 00:45:04,494
You didn't! Because it's not there!

538
00:45:06,121 --> 00:45:07,122
What?

539
00:45:07,747 --> 00:45:09,874
Are you suggesting the core...

540
00:45:10,125 --> 00:45:12,335
What, exploded?

541
00:45:15,130 --> 00:45:16,131
Yes.

542
00:45:19,134 --> 00:45:20,135
(DYATLOV SIGHS)

543
00:45:25,140 --> 00:45:26,141
SITNIKOV.

544
00:45:27,309 --> 00:45:29,144
You're a nuclear engineer. So am I.

545
00:45:30,061 --> 00:45:35,275
So please tell me how
an RBMK reactor core explodes.

546
00:45:36,401 --> 00:45:39,529
Not a meltdown, an explosion.

547
00:45:40,530 --> 00:45:41,740
I'd love to know.

548
00:45:42,782 --> 00:45:43,783
I can't.

549
00:45:45,035 --> 00:45:46,036
Are you stupid?

550
00:45:47,787 --> 00:45:48,788
No.

551
00:45:49,122 --> 00:45:50,248
Then why can't you?

552
00:45:52,083 --> 00:45:53,084
I...

553
00:45:55,629 --> 00:45:57,797
I don't see how it could explode...

554
00:46:00,050 --> 00:46:01,051
But it did.

555
00:46:01,134 --> 00:46:02,135
-(BANGS ON TABLE)
-DYATLOV: Enough!

556
00:46:02,719 --> 00:46:04,387
I'll go up to the vent block roof.

557
00:46:04,471 --> 00:46:07,140
From there, you can look right
down into reactor Building Four.

558
00:46:07,349 --> 00:46:08,475
I'll see it with my own...

559
00:46:10,477 --> 00:46:11,603
My own eyes.

560
00:46:15,482 --> 00:46:16,483
(GROANS)

561
00:46:17,359 --> 00:46:18,568
I apologize.

562
00:46:20,570 --> 00:46:21,946
Guards! Guards!

563
00:46:23,365 --> 00:46:26,326
Get him to a medic, or the hospital!
Whatever he needs!

564
00:46:34,376 --> 00:46:35,669
(DYATLOV GROANING)

565
00:46:42,967 --> 00:46:45,720
The feed water.
Been around it all night.

566
00:46:48,431 --> 00:46:49,432
You go, then.

567
00:46:53,186 --> 00:46:54,187
What?

568
00:46:54,479 --> 00:46:57,190
Go to the vent block roof
and report back what you see.

569
00:46:57,273 --> 00:46:58,274
No.

570
00:47:02,237 --> 00:47:03,697
No, I won't do that.

571
00:47:04,698 --> 00:47:05,949
Of course you will.

572
00:47:11,121 --> 00:47:12,163
You'll be fine.

573
00:47:13,081 --> 00:47:14,082
You'll see.

574
00:47:15,291 --> 00:47:16,292
Come on.

575
00:47:36,312 --> 00:47:37,522
(AKIMOV PANTING)

576
00:47:58,668 --> 00:47:59,669
Okay.

577
00:48:01,629 --> 00:48:02,672
Let's begin.

578
00:48:07,093 --> 00:48:08,094
(CREAKING)

579
00:48:11,181 --> 00:48:12,182
Leonid.

580
00:48:16,519 --> 00:48:17,520
Leonid.

581
00:48:24,152 --> 00:48:25,153
(TOPTUNOV GROANS)

582
00:48:26,237 --> 00:48:27,322
AKIMOV: It's all the way, okay?

583
00:48:28,364 --> 00:48:29,783
-All the way open.
-(SOBS)

584
00:48:39,375 --> 00:48:40,376
I'm sorry.

585
00:48:41,711 --> 00:48:42,754
(SOBBING)

586
00:48:44,464 --> 00:48:46,007
There's nothing to be sorry for.

587
00:48:46,716 --> 00:48:49,469
I told you. We did nothing wrong.

588
00:48:52,388 --> 00:48:53,515
But we did.

589
00:49:04,275 --> 00:49:05,527
(CONTINUES SOBBING)

590
00:49:10,740 --> 00:49:11,741
(DOOR OPENS)

591
00:49:32,971 --> 00:49:33,972
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

592
00:50:46,836 --> 00:50:47,879
(INAUDIBLE)

593
00:50:53,259 --> 00:50:54,260
(GASPS)

594
00:51:26,793 --> 00:51:27,919
(INAUDIBLE)

595
00:51:36,135 --> 00:51:37,512
(FOOTSTEPS)

596
00:51:48,147 --> 00:51:49,148
(MAN SHOUTS INDISTINCTLY)

597
00:51:55,655 --> 00:51:57,490
MAN: Get everyone
in the infirmary up there.

598
00:52:01,452 --> 00:52:02,829
(SIRENS WAILING)

599
00:52:19,595 --> 00:52:21,597
(PHONE RINGING)

600
00:52:27,145 --> 00:52:28,146
(GRUNTS)

601
00:52:37,864 --> 00:52:39,282
(PHONE CONTINUES RINGING)

602
00:52:42,076 --> 00:52:43,077
Hello?

603
00:52:43,161 --> 00:52:45,288
-MAN: (OVER PHONE) Valery Legasov?
-Yes.

604
00:52:45,371 --> 00:52:47,874
You are the Legasov who is
the First Deputy Director

605
00:52:47,957 --> 00:52:50,460
of the Kurchatov Institute
of Atomic Energy?

606
00:52:50,543 --> 00:52:52,712
-I am. Who am I speaking...
-This is Boris Shcherbina,

607
00:52:53,129 --> 00:52:55,131
Deputy Chairman of
the Council of Ministers

608
00:52:55,214 --> 00:52:57,300
and head of the Bureau
for Fuel and Energy.

609
00:52:58,217 --> 00:53:01,512
There's been an accident
at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant.

610
00:53:02,513 --> 00:53:03,514
How bad is it?

611
00:53:04,182 --> 00:53:06,225
No, no need to panic.
There was a fire.

612
00:53:06,309 --> 00:53:09,103
It's mostly put out.
The system control tank exploded.

613
00:53:09,395 --> 00:53:11,064
"Control system tank."

614
00:53:11,397 --> 00:53:12,482
And the core?

615
00:53:12,899 --> 00:53:15,234
We've ordered them
to continuously pump water.

616
00:53:15,943 --> 00:53:18,321
Yes, I see. Any contamination?

617
00:53:18,821 --> 00:53:21,491
It's mild. The plant manager,
Bryukhanov, is reporting

618
00:53:21,574 --> 00:53:23,242
3.6 roentgen per hour.

619
00:53:23,326 --> 00:53:25,411
That's actually significant.
You should evacuate the...

620
00:53:25,495 --> 00:53:28,915
You're an expert on
RBMK reactors, correct?

621
00:53:30,291 --> 00:53:32,919
-Yes. I've studied...
-General Secretary Gorbachev

622
00:53:33,002 --> 00:53:35,671
has appointed a committee
to manage the accident.

623
00:53:36,172 --> 00:53:37,173
You're on it.

624
00:53:38,132 --> 00:53:39,884
We'll convene at 2:00 this afternoon.

625
00:53:40,384 --> 00:53:43,513
That late? Forgive me,
but don't you think,

626
00:53:43,596 --> 00:53:45,389
given the amount of radiation,
that it would be...

627
00:53:45,473 --> 00:53:48,601
Legasov, you're on this committee
to answer direct questions

628
00:53:48,684 --> 00:53:50,895
about the function of an RBMK reactor,

629
00:53:51,062 --> 00:53:54,148
if they should happen to arise.
Nothing else,

630
00:53:54,357 --> 00:53:56,442
certainly not policy.
Do you understand?

631
00:53:57,026 --> 00:53:59,112
-Yes, of course. I didn't mean to...
-(LINE DISCONNECTS)

632
00:53:59,195 --> 00:54:00,947
(INHALES AND EXHALES DEEPLY)

633
00:54:06,661 --> 00:54:07,745
(SIGHS)

634
00:54:22,760 --> 00:54:23,970
(VALVE CREAKING)

635
00:54:25,388 --> 00:54:26,597
(AKIMOV PANTING)

636
00:54:31,394 --> 00:54:32,478
(VALVES CREAKING)

637
00:55:31,704 --> 00:55:32,830
(CHILDREN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

